properties.review_text_published: THE best way to experience Spiti. Have been to Spiti twice with them now(Kinnaur tour and Kaleidoscope tour) and both the times the trip was as smooth as it can be. They ensure proper and timely communication before the trip starts and mantain it until after the trip ends. Top notch hospitality and every person from ecosphere super polite. There are two very unique aspects of the experience and what makes them different from any other tour operator. Firstly, the guide who accompanies for most of the trip is a local person from Spiti valley. This is a good contrast from other operators because with a local guide, you get to learn about culture, practices, and get any other question answered which an outsider wouldn't know. Secondly, a authentic true-to-roots village homestay in Demul, which is a part of their itinerary is a very unique and a rewarding experience. I felt Demul is also probably the best place in Spiti tour to watch a crystal clear night sky(if weather permits). Ecosphere also have a not-for-profit wing, so do ensure you talk to them about it as well. Highly recommended. A must-have experience of a lifetime.

properties.review_text_published:
Unnecessarily expensive. The estate tour costs 500 per head, so we paid 2000rs for the tour for 4 of us. The property manager went with us in our own car and we went to a lake and a viewpoint. Along with a museum, the entire tour took approx 1h30mins. The place is very neatly mantained, and the staff is friendly and they answer any and all questions related to coffee. However, 500per head is too expensive and not worth the experience, if you've already been to and stayed in good coffee estates in other places like Coorg, Chikmaglur or Wayanad. You get to experience the same thing for free there along with the stay. So if you have been to a plantation before anytime, this place could be skipped.
PS: For a 500rs charge, the least the property owner could do is provide a sample of free coffee to taste. Maybe put that in thermos and serve it near the lake. Right now, with our own car going in muddy roads, with nothing complimentary at all, I don't think that price point has much to offer to visitors.

We didn't do the horse riding experience, and I believe that could be interesting, but they don't allow to get off the horse near the lake for entire duration of the 30min tour costing 1700pp. Having been to the lake, i can say that I personally wouldn't have enjoyed that tour at that price as well.

properties.review_text_published:
The management is helpful, attentive and polite. The food was very tasty and had decent variety both for breakfast and dinner. If one doesn't get the chance to take the forest safari, they can also opt for a Jeep ride through the nearby jungle road. While it doesn't take you offroad like official safari rides, animals like  elephant, deers etc are easily spotted. The evening Jeep ride is a good option to consider if one doesn't get to take the official safari during their trip. But if someone has already visited the jungle through safari, then this option could be skipped. The property is very close to kuruvadweep, which is a major tourist attraction.

Now to the bad part. Rooms are also neatly mantained, beds are comfortable and the views are ok (not amazing) but the jacuzzi room is a complete waste of money. 1/5 rating for the room. Jacuzzi tub is placed in a very dingy location, where dirty water drips from the top. Zero privacy thanks to wooden walls and the placement of the tub makes one claustrophobic. It's dingy and looks cheap. The washroom and the interiors however were perfect and well built. So anyone reading the review so far, I'd recommended not wasting any money on jacuzzi room, but normal rooms are pretty good, location is amazing and staff is courteous. The pool is ok. One can go to a peaceful walk to the nearby Kabini river as well.

There is also slight negligence regarding mask wearing. Good majority of people in management wear them properly but some don't.

properties.review_text_published: 5/5 staff friendliness and service. Food was good. Place is very mantained and staff seems to be following social distancing, masking covid related precautions.

A very pleasant experience and a rare find in the area. Perfect for a weekend getaway and a relaxing experience. There is a bit of mantainence needed for the interiors and washrooms, but overall it was a 5/5 experience for us. The staff is very friendly and the food is delicious.

The entrance to the property is via a 300-400m paved road through a farm and as expected, it is far off from any noise pollution. There are limited rooms on the property, which is a very good thing. Interior furnitures are mantained in good condition and beds are comfortable.

Do ask the management there for activities nearby and go for a short morning walk/trek and evening lepoard safari. Both the experiences would be one of a kind and totally worth the buck.

I would personally have loved to have a relaxing hot shower but the fixtures weren't mantained enough, and the rooms could need a little more furniture, maybe a table and two chairs at least to keep stuff and hang stuff somewhere. I am not complaining given the price point of the rooms, but even at a slightly higher price, I would have liked to have these basic necessities fulfilled.

I'll recommend the place for isolation, experience and friendliness of the staff and management. Comfort in rooms is a compromise to be honest, but still worth the overall experience. Will be visiting again sometime.

The goosebumps we got when driving in the gypsy car on the stone hills is also a one of a kind, and a must-try lifetime experience.
Although finding/spotting wildlife is always hit and miss situation, but Shahrukh took all the efforts one could, in an attempt to spot cheetah. The binoculars provided during safari were also in good condition and were of professional quality.

Although personally a bit skeptical at first, I now believe that this experience adds more to what a forest safari can offer, as it takes you through isolated places as well as some rural villages, giving a glimpse of local culture as well. Highly recommended.
In my opinion, bothforest Safari and Shahrukh's safari (not any other)  should be tried to have a complete and rich experience.

Update: Revised my rating upon clarification by the team managing the place. But that still does not justify the discrimination I was subjected to. Will definitely visit again, hoping that things have changed since my last visit.
My experience:
The place is beautifully maintained but that does NOT matter. Indians are not allowed in the place. The guard outside lied to me and made an excuse that some construction work is going on and the garden is closed. After some time I saw some foreigners going in. This discrimination is not spiritual and definitely not wise ( Guard even tried to stop an Indian origin couple from UK ). It took some confrontation from their part before he let us in. Im appalled to see a place like this in India. Even though after a discussion, I was allowed inside but by that time I had completely lost the interest and the feeling of simply sitting quietly there and enjoying the view. Owner should put a banner that it's a private property or that explicitly foreign passport holders are allowed, instead of branding as a tourist attraction( I came through Google maps). Anyone against this discrimination shouldn't be going there.
